[2] Greece
Date: 10 Aug 2018
Source: Punchng [edited]
https://punchng.com/three-dead-60-infected-as-nile-fever-hits-greece/


Three people have died from West Nile fever after an outbreak in Athens that has infected 60 people this year [2018], Greek authorities said on Friday [10 Aug 2018], indicating they were monitoring the situation carefully. "Since last week, we have registered 17 new cases," of the mosquitoborne disease, the Greek Centre for Disease Control and Prevention (Keelpno) said.

A total of 60 cases have been recorded since the start of the year [2018], with 16 people still in hospital, including 4 in intensive care, Keelpno added. The bulk of infections have occurred within the past month [mid July to early August 2018]. "That is why we are warning the public," an official said. The cases, mostly in the western suburbs of Athens, mark a reappearance of the virus after an outbreak last year [2017] when Greek authorities registered 48 cases resulting in 5 deaths.

The virus can cause flulike symptoms, but in extreme cases, it can result in tremors, fever, coma and a lethal swelling of the brain tissue, known as encephalitis. It can also cause meningitis. First discovered in Uganda in 1937, the virus is carried by birds and spread to humans by mosquitoes. It is indigenous to Africa, Asia, Europe and Australia.

"It is necessary that health professionals and national and local authorities are vigilant because there is no way of predicting which regions the virus could spread to," said Keelpno. Cases of the West Nile virus have also been reported in 2018 in Hungary, Italy, Romania and Serbia, according to data from the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control.

